   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="essay">
            <head>
               <bibl>
                  <author type="writer">
                     <name>
                        <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Elizabeth Inchbald</ref>
                     </name>
                  </author>
                  <title type="main" level="a">REMARKS [on <hi rendition="#italics"><ref
                           target="people.html#JohnKingofEngland">King John</ref></hi>].<hi
                        rendition="#sup">
                        <note>&quot;Remarks.&quot; <hi rendition="#italics"><ref
                                 target="people.html#JohnKingofEngland">King John</ref>; A
                              Historical Play, In Five Acts; By <ref
                                 target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">William Shakspeare</ref>.
                              As Performed at the Theatre Royal, Covent Garden. Printed Under the
                              Authority of the Managers From the Prompt Book. With Remarks by <ref
                                 target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs. Inchbald</ref></hi>. London:
                           Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees, and Orme, Paternoster Row, pp. 3-5. <hi
                              rendition="#italics"><title level="m">The British Theatre; or, A
                                 Collection of Plays, Which Are Acted At the Theatres Royal, Drury
                                 Lane, Covent Garden, and Haymarket. Printed Under the Authority of
                                 the Managers from the Prompt Books. With Biographical and Critical
                                 Remarks, by <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs.
                                    Inchbald.</ref></title></hi> In Twenty-Five Volumes. Vol. I. <hi
                              rendition="#italics"><title>Comedy of Errors</title></hi>. <hi
                              rendition="#italics"><title>Romeo and Juliet</title></hi>. <hi
                              rendition="#italics"><title>Hamlet</title></hi>. <hi
                              rendition="#italics"><title>King John</title></hi>. <hi
                              rendition="#italics"><title>King Richard III</title></hi>. London:
                           Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees, and Orme, 1808. <hi
                              rendition="#italics"><title>King John</title></hi> was first staged in
                           London sometime in the mid-1590s. Laura DeWitt and Mary A. Waters
                           co-edited this essay for <hi rendition="#italics">The Criticism
                              Archive</hi>.</note>
                     </hi>
                     <lb rendition="#center"/>______</title>
               </bibl>
            </head>
            <p>This tragedy is one amongst <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam"
                  >Shakspeare</ref>&apos;s dramas, which requires, in representation, such eminent
               powers of acting, that it is scarcely ever brought upon the stage, but when a theatre
               has to boast of performers highly gifted in their art.</p>

            <p>The part of <ref target="people.html#JohnKingofEngland">King John</ref> is held most
               difficult to perform. <ref target="people.html#JohnKingofEngland">John</ref> is no
               hero, and yet he is a murderer&#8212;his best actions are debased by meanness,
               deceit, or cowardice, and yet he is a king. Here is then to be pourtrayed, thirst of
               blood, without thirst of fame; and dignity of person, with a groveling mind.</p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#GarrickDavid">Garrick</ref> was so little satisfied with his
               own performance of this character, that, after playing it with cold approbation from
               the audience, he changed it for the illegitimate Faulconbridge;<hi rendition="#sup"
                     ><note>In <ref target="people.html#GarrickDavid">Garrick</ref>&apos;s 1755
                     production at Drury Lane, <ref target="people.html#GarrickDavid">Garrick</ref>
                     switched roles with <ref target="people.html#SheridanThomas">Thomas
                        Sheridan</ref> so that the latter would take on the role of <ref
                        target="people.html#JohnKingofEngland">King John</ref>, while <ref
                        target="people.html#GarrickDavid">Garrick</ref> assumed the role of Philip
                     Faulconbridge, the illegitimate son of <ref
                        target="people.html#RichardIKingofEngland">King Richard I</ref>, elder
                     brother of <ref target="people.html#JohnKingofEngland">King John</ref>. <ref
                        target="people.html#GarrickDavid">Garrick</ref> was unsuccessful in
                     attaining the strong physical presence necessary to depict the humor and
                     romantic gallantry of Faulconbridge, and in order to lessen his own deficits,
                     he chose an actor particularly meagre in appearance to play his
                     half-brother.</note></hi> where nature forced him to oppose the author&apos;s
               meaning by a diminutive person, though art did all its wonders in his favour.</p>

            <p>The genius of <ref target="people.html#KembleJohn">Kemble</ref> gleams terrific
               through the gloomy <ref target="people.html#JohnKingofEngland">John</ref>. No auditor
               can hear him call for his <quote><lg type="stanza">
                     <l>Kingdom&apos;s rivers to take their course</l>
                     <l>Through his burn&apos;d bosom,<hi rendition="#sup"><note place="foot"><hi
                                 rendition="#italics"><title><ref
                                       target="people.html#JohnKingofEngland">King
                                    John</ref></title></hi>, Act V, scene vii.</note></hi></l>
                  </lg></quote> and not feel for that moment parched with a scorching fever.</p>
            <fw type="sig"><hi rendition="#smcaps">b 2</hi></fw>
            <pb n="4"/>

            <p>Yet, in a previous scene with <ref target="people.html#BurghHubert">Hubert</ref>, by
               suffering his auditors to get before him, as it were, he fails of perfection in the
               part. An attentive audience is never dull of comprehension; and, however swiftly an
               actor proceeds, will follow close: but if permitted to gain ground of him, and
               penetrate the secret he should disclose, he gives up his prerogative by dallying with
               the impatient, who dive into impending events, with fatal consequence to all scenic
               deception.</p>

            <p>Though <ref target="people.html#BurghHubert">Hubert</ref> sinks in importance by not
               being of the blood royal in this play, his character is illustrious from his virtue.
                  <ref target="people.html#CookeGeorge">Cooke</ref>, in the habit of performing
               characters far superior, elevates <ref target="people.html#BurghHubert">Hubert</ref>
               so much above the level where performers in general place him, that he displays, in
               this single instance, abating every other, abilities of the very first class. </p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#ConstanceDuchessofBrittany">Constance</ref> is the favourite
               part both of the poet and the audience; and she has been highly fortunate under the
               protection of the actress. It was the part in which that idol of the public, <ref
                  target="people.html#CibberSusannah">Mrs. Cibber</ref>, was most of all adored; and
               the following lines, uttered by <ref target="people.html#SiddonsSarah">Mrs.
                  Siddons</ref> in <ref target="people.html#ConstanceDuchessofBrittany"
                  >Constance</ref>, <quote><lg type="stanza">
                     <l>&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;Here I and sorrow sit: </l>
                     <l>This is my throne, bid kings come bow to it,<hi rendition="#sup"><note><hi
                                 rendition="#italics"><title><ref
                                       target="people.html#JohnKingofEngland">King
                                    John</ref></title></hi>, Act III, scene i.</note></hi>
                     </l>
                  </lg></quote> seem like a triumphant reference to her own potent skill in the
               delineation of woe, as well as to the agonizing sufferings of the mother of young
                  <ref target="people.html#ArthurI">Arthur</ref>.</p>

            <p>Faulconbridge, one of the brightest testimonies of <ref
                  target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">Shakspeare</ref>&apos;s comic power, is
               excellent relief to that part of the tragedy which may be styled more dull <pb n="5"
               />than pathetic. <ref target="people.html#KembleCharles">Mr. C. Kemble</ref>
               personates this child of love, as <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam"
                  >Shakspeare</ref> himself could wish.&#8212;If those who remember <ref
                  target="people.html#GarrickDavid">Garrick</ref> in the part complain of <ref
                  target="people.html#KembleCharles">C. Kemble</ref>&apos;s inferior gaiety and
               spirit, the inferiority is granted. Still, he would be something nearer an equality
               with this great archetype of actors, could but those critics recall <hi
                  rendition="#italics">their</hi> gaiety and spirit, which, in their juvenile days,
               inspired them with the ardour to admire. </p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#ArthurI">Prince Arthur</ref> is of more importance than
               either manager or actors generally conceive. They seldom care whether a princely or
               plebeian child is to perform the part; whether from feature, or from voice, <ref
                  target="people.html#ArthurI">Arthur</ref> shall belie his royal birth, and take
               away all sympathy in his own and his mother&apos;s sufferings. </p>

            <p>Though <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">Shakspeare</ref>&apos;s
                  <title>King John</title> is inferior to many of his plays, yet it contains some
               poetic passages, and some whole scenes, written with his hand, beyond all power of
               forgery.</p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#TheobaldLewis">Theobald</ref> says, in his commentaries on
               this drama, &quot;The action of the play begins at the thirty-fourth year of the <ref
                  target="people.html#JohnKingofEngland">King</ref>&apos;s life, and takes in only
               some transactions of his reign to the time of his demise, being an interval of about
               seventeen years.&quot;<hi rendition="#sup"><note place="foot"><ref
                        target="people.html#TheobaldLewis">Lewis Theobald</ref>&apos;s comment,
                     perhaps quoted from <ref target="people.html#ReedIsaac">Isaac Reed</ref>&apos;s
                     1806 edition of <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The Plays of <ref
                              target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">William Shakspeare</ref>, With
                           the Corrections and Illustrations of Various Commentators, to Which are
                           Added Notes by <ref target="people.html#JohnsonSamuel">S. Johnson</ref>
                           and <ref target="people.html#SteevensGeorge">G.
                        Steevens</ref></title></hi>, vol. 7, page 281.</note></hi><fw type="sig"><hi
                     rendition="#smcaps">b 3</hi></fw></p>
         </div>
